WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.440
Have you ever felt that when you are in your own house, cooking for yourself, that you

00:00:11.440 --> 00:00:14.240
feel too comfortable?

00:00:14.240 --> 00:00:18.879
So comfortable that you might end up with a sad sandwich?

00:00:18.879 --> 00:00:21.760
Well, this happens to me too.

00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:28.799
But, when my husband joins the party, it's totally taco night.

00:00:28.799 --> 00:00:34.880
Of course, when you have more help in the kitchen, the result is much better.

00:00:34.880 --> 00:00:42.200
Sadly, obviously, this is not always the case, because working as a team can be challenging

00:00:42.200 --> 00:00:43.200
too.

00:00:43.200 --> 00:00:49.439
Just imagine a group of friends trying to cook together, they are used to different

00:00:49.439 --> 00:00:55.160
things, they are used to use different tools, and if they are not all on the same page,

00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:56.799
it could be a disaster.

00:00:56.799 --> 00:01:05.480
Well, this often happens when you put data professionals and infrastructure engineers

00:01:05.480 --> 00:01:07.760
to work together.

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:15.199
But if they speak the same language, they are said to build successful products.

00:01:15.199 --> 00:01:21.040
In this talk, I'm going to tell you or discuss with you some of the best practices that you

00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:25.360
could follow when building Shiny applications.

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:32.120
And some of the challenges that you may face when working with interdisciplinary teams

00:01:32.120 --> 00:01:37.080
when you want to deploy Shiny applications to the cloud.

00:01:37.080 --> 00:01:42.800
I am Yvonne Carrillo-Dominguez, data engineer manager at Vixel.

00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:48.360
At Vixel, we have several teams, and I've had the opportunity to work in two of them.

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:52.080
The data science analytics and cloud computing.

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:58.239
And these two teams often collaborate together when building data products.

00:01:58.239 --> 00:02:05.160
And the story that I'm going to tell you is about this team's very first Shiny application.

00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:08.759
I've broken down this story in three parts.

00:02:08.759 --> 00:02:13.139
Product conception, development time, and going to the cloud.

00:02:13.139 --> 00:02:17.880
In each of those parts, I'm going to tell you some of the challenges that we face and

00:02:17.880 --> 00:02:19.759
how we overcome them.

00:02:19.759 --> 00:02:24.919
And spoiler alert, we should have gone to the cloud from the beginning.

00:02:24.919 --> 00:02:27.679
Let's start with the product conception.

00:02:27.679 --> 00:02:32.880
The first question that we ask is how we are going to collaborate, given that we came from

00:02:32.880 --> 00:02:36.240
the data analysis that we were doing individually.

00:02:36.240 --> 00:02:39.600
Well, now we needed to code together.

00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:42.399
You may know the answer, so I'm just going to say it.

00:02:42.399 --> 00:02:43.399
We just Git.

00:02:44.399 --> 00:02:51.080
Some of the team members were learning about Git, like how to push and pull code.

00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:58.839
Well, luckily, we had this plugin in our studio that is the learning curve.

00:02:58.839 --> 00:03:01.360
Because it can be tricky sometimes.

00:03:01.360 --> 00:03:03.279
And why use Git?

00:03:03.279 --> 00:03:09.399
Well, you want to be able to share your code, integrate everyone's contribution, and keep

00:03:09.399 --> 00:03:11.880
different versions of your code.

00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:16.199
This is on your local, but also in the Git platform.

00:03:16.199 --> 00:03:21.600
And you can use any Git platform, like GitLab, or GitHub, or Bitbucket.

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:26.160
In our case, we asked the infrastructure team which was the better tool, because what we

00:03:26.160 --> 00:03:34.039
wanted to do is just focus on the development and not worry too much about the hosting.

00:03:34.600 --> 00:03:42.759
We wanted some pipeline, some automation where we were able to push our code, and then it

00:03:42.759 --> 00:03:45.320
was going to be deployed to the cloud.

00:03:45.320 --> 00:03:51.679
So they chose GitLab because of the continuous integration and continuous development features.

00:03:51.679 --> 00:03:57.479
So in this way, they were able to use the tool that they felt more comfortable with

00:03:57.479 --> 00:04:02.039
while we were using the tool that we were comfortable with in our studio.

00:04:05.039 --> 00:04:08.039
Then we started using Golem.

00:04:08.039 --> 00:04:16.040
Golem is a Shiny framework to build production-level, robust Shiny applications.

00:04:16.040 --> 00:04:23.040
At the beginning, I wasn't very sold on using this tool because it will add a lot of R packages

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:28.040
and scaffolding code that I wasn't very sure that we were needing it.

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:31.040
But then I really liked it.

00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:39.040
It sets you a very basic web application where you can build on the top of it.

00:04:39.040 --> 00:04:46.040
And one of the things that it adds, for example, is kind of like these scripts that it will

00:04:46.040 --> 00:04:54.040
guide you step by step so you can start building your Shiny app.

00:04:54.040 --> 00:05:02.040
For example, it will help you configure your application name, your unit testing, your

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:06.040
favicon, and then it will take you to the next step.

00:05:06.040 --> 00:05:11.040
So it is a very nice tool, and I highly recommend using Golem or a framework like this one,

00:05:11.040 --> 00:05:14.040
especially if this is your first Shiny application.

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:19.040
Dependency management.

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:25.040
This is a concept that if you're not very used to it, it can be hard to understand it.

00:05:25.040 --> 00:05:27.040
But it is very useful.

00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:34.040
So we were facing the issue that maybe my code was working on my local, but it wasn't

00:05:34.040 --> 00:05:40.040
working on another team member environment, and that's because they didn't have the R

00:05:40.040 --> 00:05:42.040
package that was needed.

00:05:42.040 --> 00:05:47.040
Or maybe they have it, but it was an older version that wasn't supporting the function

00:05:47.040 --> 00:05:48.040
that I had.

00:05:48.040 --> 00:05:53.040
So for that, you want to use a tool like a dependency management tool.

00:05:53.040 --> 00:05:55.040
And there are several options.

00:05:55.040 --> 00:06:01.040
You might as well just use an R script that will call your list of dependencies, or there

00:06:01.040 --> 00:06:05.040
are more sophisticated options like background or RMP.

00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:14.040
Whatever the option you choose, try to do it from the beginning so you won't have to

00:06:14.040 --> 00:06:16.040
do some reverse engineering.

00:06:16.040 --> 00:06:21.040
Remember all the tools that you have installed and then add it to the dependency management

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:22.040
tool.

00:06:22.040 --> 00:06:25.040
If you do it from the beginning, you won't have that problem.

00:06:28.040 --> 00:06:34.040
Also, it is okay to explore and innovate or there are packages that are out there, but

00:06:34.040 --> 00:06:41.040
for your application, just add the tools that you really need for your application to run.

00:06:42.040 --> 00:06:49.040
So when it is on the cloud, you are going to use packages, just the dependencies that

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:50.040
you need.

00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:51.040
So just keep it simple.

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:58.040
Every package that you add is used, potential bugs or issues are more maintained.

00:06:58.040 --> 00:07:00.040
So it's a good idea to keep it simple.

00:07:02.040 --> 00:07:05.040
At this point, we were ready for the development time.

00:07:05.040 --> 00:07:08.040
So everything is already set up.

00:07:08.040 --> 00:07:10.040
So we were ready to build our product.

00:07:14.040 --> 00:07:18.040
So how were we going to distribute the workload?

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:22.040
Well, Golem helped you to create these Shiny modules.

00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:28.040
You can think of them as mini Shiny applications that you are going to call from the main script.

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:36.040
In our case, we had five dashboards, so we created one Shiny module per dashboard and

00:07:36.040 --> 00:07:38.040
we distributed them among the team members.

00:07:38.040 --> 00:07:44.040
The way that you are going to separate the work is going to depend on your use case,

00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:46.040
your application or your team members.

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:50.040
Integrating the backend.

00:07:50.040 --> 00:07:52.040
So this is how we did it.

00:07:53.040 --> 00:07:58.040
We collected the data and created some R data frames.

00:08:00.040 --> 00:08:05.040
Then we loaded them into an SQLite database, which is a file.

00:08:07.040 --> 00:08:09.040
And then set up the database connection.

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:14.040
We create all the queries that we needed and then connect them,

00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:18.040
connect those results to our dashboard charts.

00:08:19.040 --> 00:08:21.040
But that wasn't real data.

00:08:21.040 --> 00:08:23.040
It was just like sample data.

00:08:23.040 --> 00:08:26.040
So we needed to really be collecting data on a daily basis.

00:08:26.040 --> 00:08:33.039
We needed to build some data pipelines and then loading that data into an Amazon Redshift

00:08:33.039 --> 00:08:36.039
and then do it all over again.

00:08:36.039 --> 00:08:38.039
So what is the recommendation here?

00:08:38.039 --> 00:08:42.039
Well, connect to your database from the beginning.

00:08:42.039 --> 00:08:48.039
Even if that database does not contain all the production code, it can be sample data.

00:08:48.039 --> 00:08:55.039
But it is very important that you start building your product thinking that it's going to be in the cloud

00:08:55.039 --> 00:08:57.039
and that it's going to be in production.

00:08:59.039 --> 00:09:01.039
Keep it secure.

00:09:01.039 --> 00:09:03.039
So at the beginning, we were...

00:09:03.039 --> 00:09:05.039
This is very bad, I know.

00:09:05.039 --> 00:09:10.039
But we were hard-coding passwords, AWS keys, and sensitive information.

00:09:10.039 --> 00:09:11.039
So what happened?

00:09:11.039 --> 00:09:15.039
Every time that we were pushing database credentials,

00:09:16.039 --> 00:09:22.039
we needed to go to that database that was already compromised and change the credentials.

00:09:23.039 --> 00:09:29.039
But what if we had pushed some sensitive information that we cannot really change?

00:09:29.039 --> 00:09:34.039
Well, you need to go to Git and remove that from your code.

00:09:34.039 --> 00:09:40.039
But Git, one of the main features is that you are going to keep several versions of your code.

00:09:40.039 --> 00:09:43.039
So even, let's say that we are talking about the password,

00:09:43.039 --> 00:09:48.039
even if the latest version does not contain that password,

00:09:48.039 --> 00:09:52.039
you can just go back to the previous commit and the password is going to be there.

00:09:53.039 --> 00:09:58.039
So you have to go all the way back to the Git history where that password is present

00:09:58.039 --> 00:10:01.039
and remove all those commits from the Git history.

00:10:02.039 --> 00:10:05.039
And by doing that, you are going to remove some production code.

00:10:05.039 --> 00:10:07.039
So it's going to be a mess.

00:10:07.039 --> 00:10:08.039
So how to solve that?

00:10:08.039 --> 00:10:10.039
Well, use environment variables.

00:10:11.039 --> 00:10:16.039
You can use this .r environment file that's going to be kept in your local.

00:10:17.039 --> 00:10:19.039
That's going to have these key value pairs.

00:10:20.039 --> 00:10:24.039
And you are going to call the keys in your code like so.

00:10:26.039 --> 00:10:31.039
And not only is it going to be secure, but it's going to be ready for the cloud as well.

00:10:31.039 --> 00:10:34.039
Because what if you have a database per environment?

00:10:34.039 --> 00:10:36.039
Those credentials are going to be different.

00:10:36.039 --> 00:10:39.039
It doesn't matter because your code is already prepared.

00:10:39.039 --> 00:10:40.039
It's only using the keys.

00:10:40.039 --> 00:10:44.039
The values are different in every environment.

00:10:44.039 --> 00:10:47.039
So the only thing that you need to tell your infrastructure engineers

00:10:47.039 --> 00:10:53.039
are what are the environment variables that you need for your application to run.

00:10:53.039 --> 00:10:56.039
And they are going to set up with something similar to that.

00:10:58.039 --> 00:11:00.039
Now, going to the cloud.

00:11:00.039 --> 00:11:02.039
This is the moment of truth.

00:11:02.039 --> 00:11:07.039
Because what you want at this point is just push your code and hope it runs.

00:11:07.039 --> 00:11:10.039
You want to build, release, and run.

00:11:10.039 --> 00:11:14.039
Well, this is rare that it happens the first time.

00:11:14.039 --> 00:11:17.039
And for us, it didn't happen like the first ten times.

00:11:18.039 --> 00:11:20.039
So how we solved that?

00:11:20.039 --> 00:11:25.039
What we did is that every time we were doing a commit, we were validating that commit.

00:11:26.039 --> 00:11:34.039
GitLab has these nice pipelines where you can add some steps to validate the code that is being pushed.

00:11:34.039 --> 00:11:40.039
So, for example, what you can do is the first step, install the dependencies,

00:11:40.039 --> 00:11:42.039
package your application.

00:11:42.039 --> 00:11:46.039
And I think this was the selling point for me about Golem.

00:11:46.039 --> 00:11:49.039
Because I wasn't really sure about using it.

00:11:49.039 --> 00:11:55.039
And when I saw that Golem needs to package your application and then run it,

00:11:55.039 --> 00:11:57.039
it was weird to me.

00:11:57.039 --> 00:12:04.039
Because I was thinking like a package like dplar or ggplot that those are there for you to use it.

00:12:04.039 --> 00:12:07.039
And I didn't want my application to be out there.

00:12:07.039 --> 00:12:09.039
But don't think it like that.

00:12:10.039 --> 00:12:16.039
When you package your application, what will happen is that it will run all your code.

00:12:16.039 --> 00:12:21.039
So that means that if you forgot to add a dependency, it's going to fail.

00:12:21.039 --> 00:12:27.039
If you forgot to remove some line of code that didn't have to be there, it's going to fail.

00:12:27.039 --> 00:12:34.039
But if it can be packaged, then it means that every line of code is a working line.

00:12:34.039 --> 00:12:39.039
So that's a very good step for quality assurance.

00:12:39.039 --> 00:12:41.039
And then run your unit test.

00:12:41.039 --> 00:12:45.039
You can validate the presence of a title, a legend, or a button,

00:12:45.039 --> 00:12:50.039
just to know that your dashboard is up and running.

00:12:50.039 --> 00:12:53.039
Also, have a development cloud environment.

00:12:53.039 --> 00:12:57.039
This is an environment that is meant to be broken.

00:12:57.039 --> 00:12:59.039
So it's for you to break.

00:12:59.039 --> 00:13:06.039
And if it is not broken, then it means that you can push it to production.

00:13:06.039 --> 00:13:10.039
This is especially important when you already went live.

00:13:10.039 --> 00:13:15.039
And you can also have a middle environment, like a staging or validation,

00:13:15.039 --> 00:13:20.039
where it's going to be an exact replica of your production environment.

00:13:20.039 --> 00:13:28.039
And you can run some end-to-end testings there, just to be sure that all the functionality is there.

00:13:28.039 --> 00:13:32.039
So those are some of the best practices that you can follow.

00:13:32.039 --> 00:13:34.039
And of course, there are more.

00:13:34.039 --> 00:13:38.039
I will say that one of the biggest ones was the communication

00:13:38.039 --> 00:13:43.039
between the infrastructure engineers and the data team.

00:13:43.039 --> 00:13:48.039
So I really recommend you to get familiar with all these concepts.

00:13:48.039 --> 00:13:52.039
And I promise you that that communication will get easier.

00:13:52.039 --> 00:13:58.039
Remember, this group of friends that are in somebody else's kitchen,

00:13:58.039 --> 00:14:01.039
it might feel weird at the beginning.

00:14:01.039 --> 00:14:06.039
But once they agree on the terms that they are going to be collaborating,

00:14:06.039 --> 00:14:10.039
how they are going to collaborate, the work gets easier.

00:14:10.039 --> 00:14:14.039
And they can start working in harmony and having fun.

00:14:14.039 --> 00:14:18.039
And most importantly, have great results.

00:14:18.039 --> 00:14:20.039
Thank you.

00:14:20.039 --> 00:14:23.039
Thank you.

